# localization: see https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Localization/Guide
# RUNTIME localization (LANG and LC_*) 
#    * set locale(s) with locale.gen; locale-gen; eselect locale
#    format: locales in /etc/locale.gen (<locale name> <charset>)
#        <locale name>: (ll_CC.<charset> e.g. en_US.UTF-8) see /usr/share/i18n/locales/
#        <charset>: normally UTF-8 (and ISO-8859-1)
#        joetoo: two lines in /etc/locale.gen: 1: "en_US ISO-8859-1" and 2: "en_US.UTF-8 UTF-8"
#    * after locale-gen; eselect en_US.utf8 (sets LANG=en_US.UTF-8),
#         edit /etc/env.d/02locale to explicitly set LC_COLLATE=C, LC_CTYPE=en_US.UTF-8
#    format: use ISO 639-1 or 639-2 (ll_cc.UTF-8)
#        LC_ sets aspects, LANG sets what is not already explicity set
#        don't set LC_ALL - it overrides other LC_ settings
#        do set LC_COLLATE=C explicitly ( =C recommended for system-wide stability )
#        (Gentoo recommendation: For optimal performance and predictability, especially
#         in server environments or when dealing with scripts and utilities sensitive
#         to collation speed: Set LC_COLLATE=C. You can still set LANG or LC_CTYPE
#         to a UTF-8 locale (e.g., en_US.UTF-8) to ensure proper display of characters
#         in other contexts.)
# BUILDTIME localization (L10N and LINGUAS)
#    * set with /etc/portage/package.use/02localization (equivalent to putting in make.conf)
#    L10N is a USE_EXPAND flag group
#        format: */* L10N: en en-US (language-only and/or language-country codes)
#    LINGUAS is used as both a USE_EXPAND flag group and a gettext-specific environment variable
#            format: */* LINGUAS: en en_US (ISO 639 but omit .country-charset (ll_cc) (no trailing .UTF-8)
#            essentially expands into USE="nls-en nls-en_US"
#    see also https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki//etc/portage/make.conf#LINGUAS and #L10N
#
## This sets the language of build output to English.
## Please keep this setting intact when reporting bugs.
#LANG="en_US.UTF-8"
#LINGUAS="en_US.UTF-8"
#LC_COLLATE="C"
#LC_CTYPE=C
#LC_MESSAGES=C
